Color in life. Dorsolateral portion of body yellowish and ventrolateral portion silvery. Midlateral band silvery with bright blue iridescence. Top of head, upper and lower jaws and eyes yellowish. Infraorbital and opercular areas silvery. Tip of first anal-fin rays white. Proximal portion of dorsal-fin rays, adipose fin, base of upper caudal-fin lobe ranging from intense yellow to orange. Base of lower caudal-fin lobe yellowish (
Fig. 4
).

Males generally with dorsal, pectoral and pelvic fins longer than in females of same SL (
Fig. 6
). Males with bony hooks starting to develop with dorsal-, pectoral- and pelvic-fin relatively shorter than males with more than two well-developed hooks on anal fin.

Geographic variation. Morphometric and meristic data do not vary significantly among specimens from different locallities (
Table 1
). Specimens from rio Negro tend to be darker, with very conspicuous chromatophores around lateral line pores, and conspicuous humeral and caudal spot.
